Heyy, as a part of Ri3D Mx, we made to models for detecting the algae and the coral with YOLO, you can find them over here:

https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1hfT5lpHofYnS0lg091QNLFhQlza5YrhA?usp=drive_link

For the algae model, we achieved an impressive 99.5% mAP (Mean Average Precision), while the coral model reached 98.2% mAP. Despite these high scores, the coral model still requires significant work and further training, as it occasionally misclassifies a bumper’s numbers as coral. On the other hand, the algae model performs flawlessly.

Since this model runs with yolo you would need to run it with PhotonVision converting the .pt models into RKNN. If you agree to do it you can follow this thread:

YOLO11 in FRC Programming
Here’s a Jupyter notebook to train YOLO11 models and convert them to RKNN so they can be used by coprocessors with Rockchips, it is intended to be used with an Orange Pi 5. This notebook is based on LaviRZ’s and LevyIshai’s YOLOv8 training notebook. I’m currently a high school sophomore in my second year with FRC Team 503, Frog Force, and as I’ve been working with vision, their work with implementing YOLO in FRC has really helped me learn a lot, especially since I started learning about compute…
